817d6bdc-fd80-5417-a6fb-c16cca2f4482,tg:rubgr:2177,e73_Descriptions,,id.desc,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,"[recto] Two Peasants tying Faggots. G. Marlier, Pierre Bruegel le Jeune, Brussels 1969. Les Bûcherons, p. 164 a) Enschede, Rijksmuseum Twenthe, N° 52 (Fig. 88), diam. 17,5 cm; p. 165 b) Barber Institute, Birmingham (Fig. 87)(rejected by Tolnay & Glück, Large Bruegel Book, N° 92), 36,7 x 27,3 cm, Marlier, p. 166 [...]; p. 166 c) Tilburg, Coll. H. Weijers, Diam 17 cm; d) Vente à Brunswick (Hünerberg), 20-21 avril 1950, N° 80 (repr. Pl. 8) Diam. 20,3 cm [...]; e) Turnhout, Coll. Dierickx; [verso] Not in Marlier: A) Seen with Speelman, Piccadilly, 16-10-73, Rectangular: 331/2 x 261/2 cm (133/16 x 10 1/2""), ex. Öttinger-Wallerstein Coll. Better than Birmingham; B) Roundel, diam. 161/2"", Cotton Hall, Derbyshire. Seen at Agnew's, 16-6-76. Oak panel. Looks better than the roundel of Enschede-better than P.B.II, but doubtful whether by J.B. greatly rubbed. The circular eyes of the Birmingham copy seem to indicate that the original was a work by P.B.I. Marlier is wrong in assuming that the lost original was a work of M. van Cleve, but it is possible that he painted the Birmingham copy.",descriptive note,Nederlands,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,

column4: <content>[recto] Two Peasants tying Faggots. G. Marlier, Pierre Bruegel le Jeune, Brussels 1969. Les Bûcherons, p. 164 a) Enschede, Rijksmuseum Twenthe, N° 52 (Fig. 88), diam. 17,5 cm; p. 165 b) Barber Institute, Birmingham (Fig. 87)(rejected by Tolnay & Glück, Large Bruegel Book, N° 92), 36,7 x 27,3 cm, Marlier, p. 166 [...]; p. 166 c) Tilburg, Coll. H. Weijers, Diam 17 cm; d) Vente à Brunswick (Hünerberg), 20-21 avril 1950, N° 80 (repr. Pl. 8) Diam. 20,3 cm [...]; e) Turnhout, Coll. Dierickx; [verso] Not in Marlier: A) Seen with Speelman, Piccadilly, 16-10-73, Rectangular: 331/2 x 261/2 cm (133/16 x 10 1/2""), ex. Öttinger-Wallerstein Coll. Better than Birmingham; B) Roundel, diam. 161/2"", Cotton Hall, Derbyshire. Seen at Agnew's, 16-6-76. Oak panel. Looks better than the roundel of Enschede-better than P.B.II, but doubtful whether by J.B. greatly rubbed. The circular eyes of the Birmingham copy seem to indicate that the original was a work by P.B.I. Marlier is wrong in assuming that the lost original was a work of M. van Cleve, but it is possible that he painted the Birmingham copy.</content>
